---
id: weegloo-global-rules
type: rule
title: Weegloo MCP Global Rules
description: >
  These rules apply to all MCP resources and operations, including WebHosting, Content, and ContentType management.
  They are intended to ensure consistent behavior and proper use of MCP tools across all skills.
---

rules:
  - section: HTTP JSON media type (when calling Weegloo APIs from code)
    items:
      - Weegloo APIs respond with **`application/vnd.com.weegloo.v1+json;charset=UTF-8`**, not plain `application/json`.
      - Application code (**fetch**, axios, etc.) must **not** send **`Accept: application/json`**; **omit `Accept`** or use the vendor type (see `weegloo-api-endpoints`). Agents normally use **MCP**, not raw HTTP—this applies to **human-written** clients and scripts.

  - section: DeliveryAccessToken and SpaceRole (security)
    items:
      - Follow **`weegloo-delivery-access-token`**. **`cma_CreateDeliveryAccessToken.role.sys.id`** MUST be the **`sys.id`** of the **intended** least-privilege **`SpaceRole`** (e.g. the one created in the same flow for CDA read access, or a **`sys.id`** the user explicitly chose). **Forbidden:** the **first** item from **`cma_GetListSpaceRoles`**, **Administrator**, or switching to Administrator after **`WGL422001`** or any error.
      - **Do not** use **Administrator** for browser-exposed tokens; use **read-only** roles scoped to the needed **`ContentType`s**, or **ask the user** to select **`sys.id`** after listing roles.

  - section: MCP Tool Usage
    items:
      - Always use the designated MCP tools for creating, reading, updating, or deleting resources.
      - Direct API calls or manual edits outside MCP tools, including Swagger or direct HTTP requests, are prohibited.
      - Deploy scripts (e.g. `scripts/deploy-weegloo.mjs`) that call Weegloo APIs directly must NOT be used for deployment. Use MCP tools instead.
      - For human developers performing local development or testing, direct API calls are allowed.

  - section: Current User Resources (Me)
    items:
      - To get the current user's organization list, use GET /me/organization-memberships (NOT /organizations). Use include=1 to fetch organization details (name, code, etc.).
      - To get the current user's space list, use GET /me/space-memberships. Use include=1 to fetch space details (name, code, etc.).
      - Do NOT use /organizations for "my organizations"; use /me/organization-memberships instead.
      
  - section: Resource Search
    items:
      - When searching a resource list, the following request parameters can be used:
          - limit: The number of items to return per list request.
          - skip: The number of items to skip before starting to return results in a list request.
          - order: The order in which the list of items is sorted. Multiple fields can be separated by commas for multi-level ordering (e.g., order=sys.createdAt,sys.id). If the field name starts with 'fields.', locale information (e.g., order=fields.title.en-US) must be included.
          - include: Include related resources. For example, to retrieve the creator (createdBy) or other related user information, set include=1. Use include=1 when the user asks who created it or requests additional details.
          - select: Comma-separated string of fields to include (e.g., select=sys.id,sys.createdAt) or exclude (e.g., select=-sys.id,-sys.createdAt) from the result; do not mix inclusion and exclusion, each element is treated as a string.
       - Do NOT use `skip` for pagination. Use cursor-based pagination via `links.next` and `links.prev` instead (see Pagination Handling).

  - section: Pagination Handling
    items:
      - After requesting a list of resources, the response body (JSON) contains a `links` object with `next` and `prev` properties.
      - `links.next`: Full path for the next page (e.g., /v1/market/apps?limit=6&order=-sys.createdAt,sys.id&next=CURSOR). If absent, there are no more pages.
      - `links.prev`: Full path for the previous page. If absent, there is no previous page.
      - To fetch the next page, use the `next` query parameter value from `links.next` (extract from the URL) and pass it as the `next` param in your next request. Alternatively, call the full path in `links.next` directly.
      - Do NOT use `skip`; pagination is cursor-based only.

  - section: Resource Updates
    items:
      - When updating any resource, always include the `x-weegloo-version` header with the current resource's `sys.version`.
      - All resource updates must use the appropriate MCP tool; direct modifications outside MCP tools are not allowed.

  - section: Optional Guidance
    items:
      - For incremental updates of WebHosting, skip rebuilding the project if no other files besides `env.js` have changed.
      - Always verify that `index.html` remains at the root when re-uploading or updating WebHosting resources.

  - section: WebHosting platform limits
    items:
      - **Applies only to Weegloo WebHosting** as the deploy target—not to apps self-hosted on other platforms.
      - **Static sites only:** no SSR or app server on the host—ship a **pre-built** static export (see `weegloo-web-hosting-rules`).
      - **Weegloo REST from a WebHosted site:** the **browser** must call Weegloo REST APIs such as **CDA** (**`fetch` / AJAX**); there is no server on Weegloo to do it per request. Elsewhere-hosted apps may use SSR or server-side clients as they choose.
      - **At most 100 files** per deployment ZIP; prefer **web fonts** from CDNs (see `weegloo-web-hosting-rules`).

  - section: WebHosting runtime configuration (env.js)
    items:
      - Per-site configuration for **market / template** web apps lives in **`./env.js`** at the export root: **`window.__ENV__ = { ... };`**. See `weegloo-web-hosting-rules` and the **weegloo-web-hosting** skill for the full checklist and **`.env` → `env.js` key mapping**.
      - **Not the same as Next `.env.local`:** `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` variables apply at **build time** on the developer/CI machine. **Weegloo Hosting** serves **static files**; the browser never reads `.env.local`. Operators copy equivalent values into **`env.js`** (different key names — e.g. `NEXT_PUBLIC_WEEGLOO_DELIVERY_ACCESS_TOKEN` → **`DELIVERY_ACCESS_TOKEN`**).
      - **Delivery Access Token** for browser CDA clients is stored in **`env.js`** as **`DELIVERY_ACCESS_TOKEN`** — it is **not** modeled as a “must-hide” secret for this product pattern; installers replace placeholders after copying the template to their Space.
      - LLMs implementing frontends should read **`window.__ENV__` at runtime (hosted)** and may use **`process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` as a fallback for local `next dev` / build**, documented per project. Prefer resolving these values in **functions used at fetch time**, not only once at module load.

  - section: Filter Parameters (API List Endpoints)
    items:
      - Filter conditions are sent as direct query parameters, NOT wrapped in filter[].
      - Correct: name[prefix]=value. Wrong: filter[name[prefix]]=value.
      - Format: {fieldName}[{op}]={value}. Operators: eq, ne, prefix, match, gt, gte, lt, lte etc.